40.title: Stomach Virus
dlg:
Results to expect:

  • Normal:
    Skin fold retracts immediately.

  • Mild or moderate dehydration:
    Skin fold is visible for less than 2 seconds while retracting.

  • Severe dehydration:
    Skin fold visible for longer than 2 seconds while retracting.

0.header:
Stomach flu is a viral inflammation of the stomach and intestines.

Symptoms of stomach virus usually appear within 4 - 48 hours after exposure to the viral contaminated food or water.



Let's see if you need to go to the hospital right away or if it is something you can take care of yourself.

1.header:
Alright.
Assuming you are having diarrhea at the moment.

The important thing with stomach virus illness is to make sure you are not looking at dehydration or any other potentially life threatening situation.

Let's start with that.

2.header:
In addition to the diarrhea, do you also have blood in the stool?

Or mucus in the stool?

3.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • It may not be of viral origin.

  • You are possibly looking at a bacterial or parasitic cause of stomach inflammation.

  • E.coli, Salmonella, Shigella comes to mind. You will have to go to the emergency room or urgent care clinic for stool testings and even documentation.

  • You may have to be given antibiotic or antiparasitic medication depending on the stool culture and other clinic evaluations. Don't try to ride this out.

  • In viral infections, stools rarely contain mucus or blood.

  • All patients with bloody diarrhea will have to be tested for E. coli at a minimum.

4.header: What about fever or chills?

5.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

6.header:
Are you feeling faint, dizzy?

Or confused?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Trending towards dehydration.

8.header: Does your mouth feel dry or sticky?

9.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible dehydration territory.

Signs of dehydration:

  • Feeling lethargic
  • Low blood pressure
  • Dry mouth
  • Sticky mouth

10.header: Does your eyes look sunken?

11.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a possible dehydration.

Signs of dehydration:

  • Feeling lethargic
  • Low blood pressure
  • Dry mouth
  • Sticky mouth
  • Sunken eyes

12.header: Have you had a urine output the past 8 hours or so?

13.header: Do you feel your heart pounding or racing?

14.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible sign of dehydration.

15.header:
Pinch the skin of the stomach or thigh using the thumb and a bent forefinger.

Did the skin get back to normal immediately after releasing it?

This is known as the 'Pinch test'. Though it is used in children, but you can try it for yourself.

16.header:
No?
If you are not dehydrated, the skin fold should retract immediately.

Results to expect:

  • Normal:
    Skin fold retracts immediately.

  • Mild or moderate dehydration:
    Skin fold is visible for less than 2 seconds while retracting.

  • Severe dehydration:
    Skin fold visible for longer than 2 seconds while retracting.

17.header:
Dehydration is a life threatening emergency.

If you are looking at dehydration, go to the emergency room or the nearest urgent care clinic. Do not delay.

If you don't think you are dehydrated, let's continue. If you answered 'Yes' to the 'Pinch test' question, tap on the 'FYI' button below to see the result to expect in case you want to try it later.

20.header:
Alright.
Diarrhea can be caused by many things, even nerve problems.

Let's narrow it down to stomach flu as much as possible. Then you will see if you can ride it out or need to go to the doctor.

21.header: Does anybody else have the same symptoms you are experiencing?

22.header:
Yes?
Stomach flu has an outbreak nature.

Gastroenteritis can affect one person or a group of people who all ate the same food or drank the same water.

23.header: Did you come in contact with similarly ill people within the last 2 days?

24.header:
Yes?
Strong possibility you are looking at stomach flu.

25.header: Did it start after you ate dairy products?

26.header:
Yes?
Possibly looking at lactose intolerance.

27.header: Are you taking any antibiotics lately?

28.header:
Yes?
Antibiotics can cause diarrhea.

29.header: Did you eat a new kind of fat-free potato chips or ice cream?

30.header:
Yes?
The olestra in these can cause diarrhea.

31.header:
Alright.
Let's see if you need to see a doctor right away or if you can ride this out.

State other things that might cause diarrhea. (See merck manual)

40.header: How many times have you used the bathroom since the diarrhea started?

41.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}times

You may be able to ride this out.

If you are seeing the signs of dehydration, you must seek urgent care or give the doctor a call.

Those signs are:

  • Dry or sticky mouth

  • Low or no urine output for 8 hrs. Urine looks dark yellow or amber

  • No tears

  • Sunken eyes

  • Increased thirst

  • Palpitations (feeling the heart pounding)

  • Confusion and dizziness

  • No sweat.

  • Dry skin that sags slowly into position when pinched up

  • Cool hands and feet.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you do or use over-the-counter to take care of this stomach flu situation that you may have.

42.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}times

Watch out for dehydration.

If you have other symptoms or feeling weak from the diarrhea, you should seek urgent care or go to the emergency room.

If you are seeing the signs of dehydration, you must seek urgent care or give the doctor a call.

Those signs are:

  • Dry or sticky mouth

  • Low or no urine output for 8 hrs. Urine looks dark yellow or amber

  • No tears

  • Sunken eyes
  • Increased thirst

  • Palpitations (feeling the heart pounding)

  • Confusion and dizziness

  • No sweat.

  • Dry skin that sags slowly into position when pinched up

  • Cool hands and feet.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you do or use over-the-counter if the list above do not apply to you.

43.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}times

Seek Urgent Care.

This may not be due to stomach flu or you have it very bad.

If you are seeing the signs of dehydration, you must seek urgent care or go to the emergency room.

Those signs are:

  • Dry or sticky mouth

  • Low or no urine output for 8 hrs. Urine looks dark yellow or amber

  • No tears

  • Sunken eyes

  • Increased thirst

  • Palpitations (feeling the heart pounding)

  • Confusion and dizziness

  • No sweat.

  • Dry skin that sags slowly into position when pinched up

  • Cool hands and feet.

0.header:
You may have eaten or drank contaminated food or water.

Let's see if you can ride this out on your own or need to go to the nearest urgent care clinic or even the emergency room.

1.header:
What make you think you have food poisoning?

You have diarrhea. Is this correct?

2.header:
Alright.
Let's make sure this diarrhea won't lead to complications such as Dehydration.

3.header: Is there blood or pus in your stools?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria or parasite cause.
  • Need documentation by health department.
  • No over-the-counter diarrhea medication for this type.

5.header:
What about diarrhea with a fever above 101.5°F
(measured orally)?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Serious case of food poisoning.
  • Require documentation by health authorities.

7.header: In addition to the diarrhea, are you feeling thirsty, dizzy or light-headed?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Signs of dehydration
  • Prefer emergency room visit.

9.header:
Is your heart racing, pounding?

Or skipping?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possibly severe dehydration.
  • Losing electrolytes

11.header: Has this diarrhea being going on for more than 3 days now?

12.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Risking dehydration.
  • May need antibiotics to take care of this.

13.header: Are you also taking medications called diuretics (water pills) right now?

14.header:
Call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may need to ask the doctor if you need to stop taking the diuretic if the diarrhea is getting severe.
  • Remember to talk to the doctor first before stopping the medication.

15.header:
Dehydration is the most common complication from food poisoning.

The goal should be to manage the diarrhea. A pharmacist will tell you how to this very soon.

20.header: Are you experiencing nausea and or vomiting?

22.header: Has this vomiting been going on for more than 24 hours now?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Risking electrolyte loss.
  • Will need anti-vomiting prescription medication.

24.header: Have you thrown up 3 or more times within the past 24 hours?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Risking dehydration.
  • Need prescription anti-vomiting medication to take care of this.
  • If office is closed, call the after-hour line. A nurse or doctor can always call in nausea medication to the pharmacy for you.

26.header: Have you been able to keep liquid down for the past 12 hours or more?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You don't want to risk dehydration.
  • Need medication to stop the nausea and vomiting.
  • If doctor office is closed, call the after-hour line. A nurse or doctor can always call in nausea medication to the pharmacy for you.

28.header:
Nausea and vomiting due to food poisoning can lead to dehydration.

It is very important you know when to seek emergency or urgent care

If it is just diarrhea and no vomiting, you may be looking at a viral case.

If it is both diarrhea and vomiting, you may be looking at a bacteria cause which will require urgent care.

Let's continue and see what we can come up with.

30.header: Stomach cramps. Are you experiencing one?

31.header:
No?
This is the most common symptom of food poisoning.

If You are not having stomach cramps or pain and think you have food poisoning, we advice you see a health care provider.

32.header: Did you start feeling sick a few hours after you ate food?

33.header:
No?
If think you have food poisoning, you will have to see a health care provider.

34.header: Is someone else that ate the same food sick?

35.header:
Seek urgent care or the emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at an outbreak if a group of you became ill after eating something.

  • Proper reporting and documentation is required in case product need to be recalled.

36.header: Are you feeling weak and very tired as a result of this?

37.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You don't know when it would stop. So seek help.
  • If you feel you can handle it let's continue.

38.header: Do you have a headache in addition to the diarrhea or vomiting?

39.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Serious case of food poisoning. Don't take it lightly if you suspect food poisoning.

40.header:
Is the food poisoning from mushrooms, fish?

Or canned food?

41.header:
Seek urgent care or the emergency room.

Here is why:

  • If it is from canned food, you will want to rule out botulism. Which, although is rare, can result in a very serious illness such as paralysis.

The bacteria that causes botulism, produce spores which survive in preserved or canned food, that was not done properly. These spores produce toxins that even a tiny amount can lead to severe cases of poisoning.

42.header:
Those were the symptoms of food poisoning.

If you suspect one and don't think you need to seek urgent care or emergency room visit let's see what a pharmacist recommend that is available over-the-counter to manage this in a symptomatic fashion.

If in doubt about seeking urgent care visit, err on the side of going to the urgent care clinic or emergency room. You don't know how long it would last.

0.header:
Let's figure out how to take care of this.

Does this look like a yeast infection?
This is a common question you are likely asking yourself.



Let's get started.

1.header: First, you will rule in or out having to seek urgent care.

2.header: Is this for a pregnant woman?

3.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Don't attempt selfcare.

4.header: Are you diabetic and you think you have a yeast infection?

5.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • It will be hard to get rid of with over-the-counter medications.
  • Will need a prescription yeast infection medication.

6.header: Do you have any fever with this suspected yeast infection?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Worse than you think.

8.header: Are you experiencing a greenish - yellow vagina discharge?

9.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a different type of infection.
  • Possibly Trichomonal vaginitis.

10.header:
What about a discharge that is watery, bloody?

Or both?

11.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May result from vulvar, vaginal, or cervical cancer

12.header: Do you have stomach pain or cramps with this suspected yeast infection?

13.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at PID (Pelvic inflammatory disease)

14.header: Has exposure to STD crossed your mind lately?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need further evaluation.

16.header: Those questions were to rule out situations that require urgent care.

20.header: Have you ever had or experienced a yeast infection before?

30.header:
Reminder:
Diagnosis of a yeast infection is best done by a healthcare professional.

This may involve physical observation, history taking, checking vaginal pH, wet mount microscopy or even culture to confirm the diagnosis.

A few more questions and we will see if you are looking at a yeast infection in the first place.

31.header: Is this a frequently reoccurring yeast infection for you?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Women with frequent recurrences require fungi culture to confirm the diagnosis.
  • Need to rule out other causes of the symptoms of vaginal infections.

33.header: Are you looking at a thin, gray discharge with a fishy odor?

34.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at bacteria vaginosis.

In bacteria vaginosis a fishy odor is present, often becoming stronger when the discharge is more alkaline—after sex and menses.

35.header:
Are you experiencing itching inside the vagina?

And at the entrance?

36.header:
Yes?
Yeast infection can cause this so also can a lot of other things.

Let's continue.

37.header:
What about burning sensation while urinating?

Or having intercourse?

38.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a yeast infection. But other things can also cause this.

Let's Continue.

39.header: Is the entrance to the vagina swollen?

41.header: Is the entrance reddish?

43.header: Looking at the discharge again, is it whitish in appearance?

50.header:
Does the discharge appear thick?

And Lumpy?
(Like cottage cheese)

51.header:
Yes?
Alright. Possibly a yeast infection.

Symptoms include:

  • Redness in vaginal/vulvar area
  • Itching, burning in vaginal/vulvar area
  • Pain during intercourse.
  • White, clumpy or chunky (cottage cheese-like), discharge
  • Increased amount of discharge.

52.header: Does the discharge stick to the vaginal wall and not easily removed?

53.header:
Yes?
Looking at a possible yeast infection discharge.

Symptoms include:

  • Redness in vaginal/vulvar area
  • Itching, burning in vaginal/vulvar area
  • Pain during intercourse.
  • White, clumpy or chunky (cottage cheese-like), discharge
  • Increased amount of discharge.
  • Discharge adheres to the vaginal walls.

54.header:
Those were signs and symptoms of a yeast infection.

If you answered "No" to the last 2 questions, you may not be looking at a yeast infection.

If you think you are looking at a yeast infection and you don't need to see a doctor, at least not yet, Let's get an over-the-counter recommendation from a pharmacist.

Or would you like to seek urgent care for this because you are still not sure it is a yeast infection?

60.header:
How bad is it?
On a scale of 1 to 10, how bad are your symptoms so far?

61.header:
You said :{{currentTemp}}

Not too bad.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter.

Would you like to do that or visit the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

62.header:
You said :{{currentTemp}}

Getting bad?

It may be better to see a doctor for a prescription medication.

If not, then let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter.

Would you like to do that or visit the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

63.header:
You said :{{currentTemp}}

Pretty bad ugh?

We strongly suggest you see a doctor for a prescription medication.

If not, then let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter.

Would you like to do that or visit the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

70.header:
See a doctor if this is your first time experiencing this.

If you've had it before, maybe you can do self care. Won't you at least like to find out from the doctor why it happened in the first place? This way you can avoid it in the future.

For instance the doctor may want to check for diseases that can lead to yeast infections like diabetes.

Moreover, it is very difficult to know if it is a yeast infection the first time around.

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you or continue with this for now?

43.title: UTI
dlg: Bacteria can get to the bladder through the tube that empties urine from the bladder called the urethra leading to an infection. Although the body has a way of getting rid of these bacteria and keeping the urinary tract kind of sterile, sometimes the bladder can get infected.

0.header:
Also know as urinary tract infection (UTI), cystitis. Let's see what to use over the counter for this.

The goal here is to act fast so the infection doesn't spread up the tract to the kidney.



Let's get started.

1.header:
Are you looking at a urinary tract infection in the first place?

We will answer that first.

2.header: Is your urine cloudy or strong?

4.header: Does it smell foul?

5.header:
Yes?

  • Describe anything that might cause that and continue

6.header: Are you seeing any blood in the urine?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need more evaluation. Do not attempt selfcare.

8.header: While urinating, do you feel pain?

10.header: What about a burning sensation?

11.header:
Yes?
Possibly UTI. Other things can cause this, let's narrow it down.

Symptoms of UTI include:

  • Cloudy and strong urine
  • Pain with urination
  • Burning sensation with urination

12.header: Any cramping in the lower middle abdomen?

13.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a urinary tract infection.

Symptoms of UTI include:

  • Cloudy and strong urine
  • Pain with urination
  • Burning sensation with urination
  • Lower abdominal cramping

14.header: Do you feel pressure in the lower part of your stomach or abdomen?

15.header:
Yes?
Possible Urinary Tract Infection.

Symptoms include:

  • Cloudy and strong urine
  • Pain with urination
  • Burning sensation with urination
  • Lower abdominal cramping
  • Pressure-like feeling in the lower part of stomach

16.header: Are you experiencing or did you experience a low grade fever?

17.header:
Yes?
Low grade fever can be a sign of UTI

18.header: Do you feel a strong need to urinate often?

19.header:
Yes?
If you have a UTI, you will feel a strong need to urinate.

20.header:
Those were the main symptoms of a urinary tract infection.

You should have an idea if you are looking at a urinary tract infection or not by now.

If you think you are looking at one, let's make sure it is not too bad and if it is, make a good decision on what to do.

30.header: Do you also have nausea and/or vomiting with this bladder pain?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • It is worse than you think.
  • Need to rule out other serious problems.

32.header: If you have fever, is it greater than 101°F ? (measured orally)

33.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a possible kidney infection.

34.header: Are you experiencing chills and shaking?

36.header: What about night sweats with this bladder pain?

37.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible kidney infection

38.header:
Is your skin flushed?

Or warm to touch?

39.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a possible kidney infection.

40.header:
Do you have abdominal pain?

Not including pain in the bladder area while urinating.

50.header: Is this abdominal pain very severe... like you can't move?

51.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible serious infection

52.header: Is this pain on the side or flank?

53.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible kidney infection.

54.header: Is this pain on the back?

55.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible kidney infection.

56.header:
Those were the signs and symptoms of a possible kidney infection.

If they did not apply to you, you may be looking at a lower urinary tract infection rather than an upper one which would have included the kidneys.

You will still need to see a doctor. A UTI is an infection, so you may need some antibiotics and none is available over-the-counter.

The pharmacist can only recommend something you can take to help with the burning pain available over the counter until you can see a doctor.

If this is a recurring thing for you, call the doctor's office or answering service and see if the doctor can call in something for you to the nearest pharmacy. Usually, the doctor will if you have been diagnosed with it before.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend or visit the nearest urgent care clinic?

60.header:
No?
Alright, we just tried to rule out kidney infections
(pylenephritis.)

You will still need to see a doctor to treat a urinary tract infection. It is an infection, so you may need antibiotics and none is available over-the-counter.

The pharmacist can only recommend something you can take to help with the burning pain until you see a healthcare provider.

If this is a recurring thing for you, call the doctor's office or answering service and see if the doctor can call in something for you to the nearest pharmacy. Usually, the doctor will if you have been diagnosed with it before.

Would you like to see what is available over the counter or visit the nearest urgent care clinic?
